    <title>Combined summary - Exploring: limiting transaction output amount as a function of total input value</title>
    <updated>2023-06-15T00:37:11.886182+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2021-August/019293.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin developers have proposed new scripting capabilities to enable rate-limiting the output amount of a transaction based on the total value of its inputs. The proposed system involves using multisig with two sets of private keys, one for sending with rate-limiting restrictions and one for sending without restrictions. This could add an additional layer of protection against attackers sweeping all a user's funds in one transaction and allow exchanges to rate-limit addresses containing large amounts of Bitcoin. The parameters defining how an output is rate-limited include block heights indicating the first and last block height of an epoch, maximum amounts that are allowed to be sent in any epoch and within the current epoch. Change outputs must also be rate-limited to properly enforce rate-limiting.In email conversations between various developers, different proposals and challenges for implementing new functionalities in Bitcoin are discussed, including rate-limiting output amounts and controlling coins with two private keys. To address privacy concerns, some suggest using clever MAST-fu in covenant schemes to accommodate the desired feature, while others propose using `nSequence` in relative-locktime mode instead of a window for implementing this functionality. However, each solution has its drawbacks, leading to potential bikeshed-painting. Further work is needed to define all validations and describe the aggregate behavior of multiple (rate-limited) inputs, proof that two rate-limited addresses cannot spend more than the sum of their individual limits. While implementation complexity may increase, the added functionality justifies this complexity.</summary>
